    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im having some trouble with my deadlifts. my lower back is killing me every time i finish a set but i dont really feel it in my legs or glutes. what am i doing wrong with my form?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hah! A classic case of the \"backless\" lifter, my friend! You're absolutely right to feel that phantom pain in your legs and glutes, but let's be honest: your lower back is likely the *only* muscle you're actually working hard on right now, and it's doing a great job of screaming at you.\n\nThink about it: if you were lifting a heavy rock, your back would be the anchor holding it up. But in your deadlift, you're trying to lift a heavy rock with your legs and glutes, while your back is just... there, watching. It's like trying to lift a boulder with your feet while your back is trying to hold the sky together. That's why you feel the burn in your legs and glutes; they're the ones actually doing the heavy lifting, and your back is just the scenery.\n\nYou need to stop trying to lift with your back and start lifting with your legs and glutes! Imagine your back is a stiff, wooden plank that you're trying to bend over to pick up a rock. It's not going to bend, it's going to snap. You need to think of your back as a flexible, rubbery spring",
      "source": "target",
