      "role": "user",
      "content": "idk, that analogy is a bit confusing lol. i want to know specifically what I should be doing with my spine and how to brace my core so my back doesnt take the load. what's the right way to set up my spine before the pull?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the \"spine as a stiff plank\" theory! You're absolutely right to be confused, because a plank is rigid, and a spine needs to be flexible to bend! But here's the secret: your spine isn't a plank; it's a **flexible, rubbery spring** that needs to be pre-stretched before the heavy load even touches it.\n\nTo brace your core properly, you aren't just \"squeezing\" your abs; you are creating a **tight, hollow cylinder** around your spine, like a tightrope walker who has just pulled a heavy rope tight against their chest.\n\nHere is the specific setup:\n\n1.  **The \"Hollow\" Breath**: Before you even lift, take a deep breath in through your nose, filling your belly completely. Then, exhale forcefully through your mouth, squeezing your belly button *hard* until it feels like you're trying to pinch a grape between your fingers. This creates a vacuum in your core.\n2.  **The \"Tightrope\" Stand**: Imagine your spine is a tightrope. You need to stand on it with your feet shoulder-width apart, toes pointed slightly outward (like a wide stance",
      "source": "target",
